    slug: 'i-and-the-village',
    description: `<p><a href="/artist/marc-chagall"><strong>Marc Chagall</strong></a> painted this dreamlike canvas in 1911, about a year after arriving in Paris from his native Belarus. A green-faced man stares at a goat, their profiles overlapping. A smaller image of a goat being milked appears on the animal's cheek. Behind them, a village with an Orthodox church floats upside down, an upside-down woman and a man with a scythe drifting past.</p>
<p>The painting blends Cubist structure with <strong>Belarusian and Jewish folklore</strong> from Chagall's childhood in Vitebsk. Green symbolizes growth and life, <a href="https://luxurywallart.com/collections/red-wall-art" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>red</strong></a> evokes warmth, <a href="https://luxurywallart.com/collections/blue-wall-art" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>blue</strong></a> suggests nostalgia. The title itself hints at the connection between artist and homeland. Scholar H.W. Janson called it "a Cubist fairy tale."</p>
<p>Chagall kept the painting until 1916, when it went to Berlin. After changing hands several times, it entered the <a href="/museum/moma"><strong>Museum of Modern Art</strong></a> collection in 1945, shortly after Chagall arrived in America as a refugee from Nazi-occupied Europe. MoMA featured it prominently in their 1946 Chagall retrospective.</p>`,
    faqs: [
      { question: "Where can I see I and the Village?", answer: "The painting hangs at the <a href=\"/museum/moma\"><strong>Museum of Modern Art</strong></a> in New York. It entered the collection in 1945, when <a href=\"/artist/marc-chagall\"><strong>Chagall</strong></a> was newly arrived as a wartime refugee." },
      { question: "What does I and the Village mean?", answer: "It reflects <a href=\"/artist/marc-chagall\"><strong>Chagall's</strong></a> memories of Vitebsk, his Belarusian hometown. The Jewish folklore, Orthodox church, and domestic animals represent shtetl life filtered through Cubist and Fauvist styles." },
      { question: "Why is the man's face green?", answer: "<a href=\"/artist/marc-chagall\"><strong>Chagall</strong></a> used symbolic color throughout his work. Green represents growth and life. The figure is believed to be a self-portrait, showing the artist connected to his village homeland." },
      { question: "What style is I and the Village?", answer: "It blends Cubism and Fauvism with folk imagery. Scholar H.W. Janson called it \"a Cubist fairy tale.\" <a href=\"/artist/marc-chagall\"><strong>Chagall</strong></a> ignored perspective and natural color to create emotional truth." }
    ]
