      { question: "How does this differ from Caravaggio's version?", answer: "<a href=\"/artist/artemisia-gentileschi\"><strong>Artemisia's</strong></a> Judith shows no hesitation. Both women strain with physical effort. The violence feels more brutal and immediate than <a href=\"/artist/caravaggio\"><strong>Caravaggio's</strong></a> psychological approach." },
      { question: "What was Artemisia Gentileschi's biography?", answer: "<a href=\"/artist/artemisia-gentileschi\"><strong>Artemisia</strong></a> was raped at 17 by her father's colleague. She pursued justice through a trial involving torture, then built a remarkable career painting powerful female subjects." },
      { question: "Why was this painting hidden for so long?", answer: "Grand Duchess of Tuscany found it too violent for public display. It remained in peripheral locations at the <a href=\"/museum/uffizi\"><strong>Uffizi</strong></a> until the 20th century brought renewed appreciation for <a href=\"/artist/artemisia-gentileschi\"><strong>Artemisia's</strong></a> work." }
