      { question: "What is Marriage A-la-Mode about?", answer: "<a href=\"/artist/william-hogarth\"><strong>Hogarth</strong></a> satirizes arranged aristocratic marriages. This scene shows a loveless couple the morning after their wedding, surrounded by symbols of debt, infidelity, and moral decay." },
      { question: "What happens in the full series?", answer: "Six paintings follow the doomed marriage: the contract signing, this morning-after scene, visits to quacks and mistresses, the husband's death in a duel, and the wife's suicide. <a href=\"/artist/william-hogarth\"><strong>Hogarth</strong></a> spared nothing." },
      { question: "How did Hogarth spread his work?", answer: "<a href=\"/artist/william-hogarth\"><strong>Hogarth</strong></a> created engravings of his paintings for mass distribution. This made social commentary accessible to middle-class audiences who couldn't afford original paintings." }
